{"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Swift Numerics Package Overview","anchor":"Swift-Numerics-Package-Overview"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Provides building blocks for generic numerical computing in Swift."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Includes a protocol called "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics\/blob\/c634b5ddcea8445244b7cde1e5deddb8adf58e37\/Sources\/RealModule\/Real.swift#L30","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" and a "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics\/blob\/c634b5ddcea8445244b7cde1e5deddb8adf58e37\/Sources\/ComplexModule\/Complex.swift#L48","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" number type."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"High-performance "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Float16"},{"type":"text","text":" type."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"The package is open-source at ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Example: The Logit function","anchor":"Example-The-Logit-function"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This example uses the "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Logit"},{"type":"text","text":" function from statistics."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Essentially, given a probability "},{"code":"p","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" in the range 0…1, returns the log of the odds, "},{"code":"log(p \/ (1 - p))","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You would implement the function like this:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["import Darwin","","func logit(_ p: Double) -> Double {","  log(p) - log1p(-p)","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"There’s a small problem: this only supports ","type":"text"},{"code":"Double","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"s. What about ","type":"text"},{"code":"Float","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"s or any other floating-point type? Our function should try to be generic.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"A reasonable first attempt might look like:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["import Darwin","","func logit<T>(_ p: T) -> T {","  log(p) - log1p(-p)","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"But this won’t compile because the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"log"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"log1p"},{"type":"text","text":" functions only make sense for a handful of floating-point types."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We need a constraint for our generic type. The Numerics module provides a "},{"code":"Real","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" protocol, which allows our code to work for any standard floating-point type, current or future. This code calls generic versions of the "},{"code":"log","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"code":"log1p","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" functions."}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["import Numerics","","func logit<NumberType: Real>(_ p: NumberType) -> NumberType {","  log(p) - log1p(-p)","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The `Real` protocol","anchor":"The-Real-protocol"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Part of Swift Numerics package","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Provides generic access to all standard floating-point capabilities.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The definition is:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["public protocol Real: FloatingPoint, AlgebraicField, RealFunctions { ... }"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Note that ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics\/blob\/5dfc460876510988560170cee3702ab01b89587a\/Sources\/RealModule\/AlgebraicField.swift#L48","type":"reference"},{"text":" and ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics\/blob\/5dfc460876510988560170cee3702ab01b89587a\/Sources\/RealModule\/RealFunctions.swift#L12","type":"reference"},{"text":" are also new protocols defined in the Numerics package. However, ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"overridingTitle":"Real","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"code":"Real","type":"codeVoice"}],"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics\/blob\/c634b5ddcea8445244b7cde1e5deddb8adf58e37\/Sources\/RealModule\/Real.swift#L30","type":"reference"},{"text":" is the one you should usually use.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Numeric Protocols in the Swift standard library","anchor":"Numeric-Protocols-in-the-Swift-standard-library"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"These are the protocols already defined in the Swift standard library:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"image","identifier":"WWDC20-10217-protocols_in_standard_lib"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This topic focuses on "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/additivearithmetic","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/signednumeric","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":", and "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/floatingpoint","isActive":true}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"AdditiveArithmetic"},{"type":"text","text":" applies to types that support addition and subtraction."}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"SignedNumeric"},{"type":"text","text":" introduces multiplication."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"FloatingPoint"},{"type":"text","text":" adds many other operations for floating-point computation. This includes comparison functions, a way to decompose numbers into an exponent and significand, and useful constants like infinity or pi."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Protocols in the Numerics package","anchor":"Protocols-in-the-Numerics-package"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The Numerics package builds on protocols already in the Swift standard library.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"overridingTitle":"AlgebraicField","type":"reference","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"AlgebraicField"}],"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics\/blob\/5dfc460876510988560170cee3702ab01b89587a\/Sources\/RealModule\/AlgebraicField.swift#L48"},{"type":"text","text":" augments "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"SignedNumeric"},{"type":"text","text":" by introducing division and reciprocation."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics\/blob\/5dfc460876510988560170cee3702ab01b89587a\/Sources\/RealModule\/ElementaryFunctions.swift#L52","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"text":" augments ","type":"text"},{"code":"AdditiveArithmetic","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" by adding a large collection of common floating-point functions, such as logarithms and trigonometric functions.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"isActive":true,"overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"code":"RealFunctions","type":"codeVoice"}],"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics\/blob\/5dfc460876510988560170cee3702ab01b89587a\/Sources\/RealModule\/RealFunctions.swift#L12","overridingTitle":"RealFunctions","type":"reference"},{"text":" extends ","type":"text"},{"code":"ElementaryFunctions","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" even further with some lesser-used functions, such as gamma and error functions.","type":"text"}]}]}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Real"},{"type":"text","text":" protocol combines all of these protocols into a single, unified concept:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"WWDC20-10217-protocols_in_numerics","type":"image"}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Implications of the `Real` protocol","anchor":"Implications-of-the-Real-protocol"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Generics constrained to ","type":"text"},{"code":"Real","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" support all standard floating-point types.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Reduces code duplication."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Simplifies maintenance.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Makes defining new numerical types easier.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The `Complex` type","anchor":"The-Complex-type"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Part of the Swift Numerics package","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Generic over any ","type":"text"},{"code":"Real","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" type, so it works for any floating-point type.","type":"text"}]}]}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["import Numerics","","let z = Complex(1.0, 2.0)  \/\/ z = 1 + 2i"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Complex"},{"type":"text","text":" defaults to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Double"},{"type":"text","text":", so the full type-annotated version of the code is:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["import Numerics","","let z: Complex<Double> = Complex(1.0, 2.0)  \/\/ z = 1 + 2i"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Generic Numerical Programming","anchor":"Generic-Numerical-Programming"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"While "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Complex"},{"type":"text","text":" is a type by itself, it also enables generic numerical programming."}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["public struct Complex<NumberType> where NumberType: Real {","\t\/\/\/ The real component","\tpublic var real: NumberType ","","\t\/\/\/ The imaginary component","\tpublic var imaginary: NumberType ","","  \/\/\/ Construct a complex number with specified real and imaginary parts","  public init (_ real: NumberType, imaginary: NumberType) { ","  \tself.real = real ","  \tself.imaginary = imaginary ","  }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"WWDC20-10217-generic_numerical_programming","type":"image"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To make complex numbers fully functional, we need to extend them with the "},{"code":"SignedNumeric","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" protocol:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["extension Complex: SignedNumeric {","\t\/\/\/ The sum of 'z' and 'w' ","  public static func +(z: Complex, w: Complex) -> Complex {","  \tComplex(z.real + w.real, z.imaginary + w.imaginary) ","  }","","  \/\/\/ The difference of 'z' and ' w' ","  public static func -(z: Complex, w: Complex) -> Complex {","  \tComplex (z.real - w.real, z.imaginary - w.imaginary) ","  }","","  \/\/\/ The product of 'z' and ","  public static func *(z: Complex, w: Complex) -> Complex { ","  \tComplex(","  \t\tz.real * w.real - z.imaginary * w.imaginary,","  \t\tz.real * w.imaginary + z.imaginary * w.real","  \t)","\t}","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"image","identifier":"WWDC20-10217-signednumeric_protocol_extension"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Complex numbers are often expressed in polar coordinates (length + phase angle):","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["extension Complex { ","  \/\/\/ The Euclidean norm (a.k.a. 2-norm) of the number.","  public var length: NumberType { ","    .hypot(real, imaginary)","  } ","","  \/\/\/ The phase (angle, or \"argument\"). ","  \/\/\/","  \/\/\/ Returns the angle (measured above the real axis) in radians. ","  public var phase: NumberType { ","  \t.atan2(y: imaginary, x: real)","  }","","  \/\/\/ A complex value with specified polar coordinates.","  public init(length: Number Type, phase: Number Type) { ","  \tself = Complex (.cos(phase), .sin(phase)).multiplied(by: length) ","  }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"WWDC20-10217-polar_complex","type":"image"}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Compatibility with C and C++","anchor":"Compatibility-with-C-and-C++"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"Complex","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is a plain struct with 2 floating-point values, so its memory layout "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"precisely"}]},{"type":"text","text":" matches the complex number types of C and C++. The following are all the same in memory:"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"Complex<Double>","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" (Swift)","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"_Complex double"},{"text":" (C)","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"std::complex<double>","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" (C++)","type":"text"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"As a result, Swift code can exchange buffers of complex numbers with C\/C++ APIs. You can just pass a pointer to a Swift "},{"code":"Complex","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" struct to a C\/C++ library that also expects a complex type."}]},{"type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Example: Using Accelerate’s BLAS functions","anchor":"Example-Using-Accelerates-BLAS-functions"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"BLAS = Basic Linear Algebra Subroutines. Apple’s implementation is written in C. Notice how the function accepts a pointer to the array of "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Complex<Double>"},{"type":"text","text":" numbers using the ampersand ("},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"&"},{"type":"text","text":") operator."}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["import Numerics","import Accelerate","","\/\/ Array of 100 random `Complex<Double>` numbers.","let z = (0 ..< 100).map {","  Complex(length: 1.0, phase: Double.random(in: -.pi ... .pi))","}","","\/\/ Compute the Euclidean norm of `z`.","let norm = cblas_dznrm2(z.count, &z, 1)"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","level":4,"text":"One Caveat","anchor":"One-Caveat"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The Numerics package treats complex infinity and NaN differently than in C or C++. This can affect code ported from C or C++.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"However, Swift’s treatment of these values is simpler and significantly more performant for multiplication and division. Below is a benchmark comparing Swift to C:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"image","identifier":"WWDC20-10217-complex_benchmark"}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Numerics is a work in progress","anchor":"Numerics-is-a-work-in-progress"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Recent additions:"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Specialized handling for integer powers.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Approximate equality."}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Numerics is developed as a community on GitHub. Some of the projects being discussed include:"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Arbitrary-precision integers.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Shaped arrays."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Decimal floating point.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"`Float16`","anchor":"Float16"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Is a new floating-point type in the Swift standard library."}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"IEEE 754 standard format.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Already available on iOS, iPadOS, tvOS, watchOS (ARM-based platforms).","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Calling convention for x86 is not yet finalized (working with Intel to fix this)."}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Is a normal floating-point type."}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Conforms to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"BinaryFloatingPoint"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"SIMDScalar"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Conforms to ","type":"text"},{"code":"Real","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" from Swift Numerics.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Supports all of the standard floating-point functions."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"If you implement the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Real","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" protocol in your code, you will automatically get support for ","type":"text"},{"code":"Float16","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Trade-offs","anchor":"Trade-offs"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Pros:"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Significant performance gains because you can fit more of them into a SIMD register or a page of memory."}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Interoperates with C\/Objective-C "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"__fp16"},{"type":"text","text":" type."}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Cons:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Low precision, small range.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Size and Constraints","anchor":"Size-and-Constraints"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Be mindful of these constraints when porting code that was originally written with "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Float"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Double"},{"type":"text","text":" in mind:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"image","identifier":"WWDC20-10217-float16_size_constraints"}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hardware Support","anchor":"Hardware-Support"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Supported (and preferred) by Apple’s GPUs.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Supported by Apple’s CPUs starting with A11 Bionic.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Scalar performance identical to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Float"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Double"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"SIMD performance is 2x that of "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Float"},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"code":"Float16","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is simulated using "},{"code":"Float","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" operations on older hardware. The results are exactly the same, but without the speedup gains."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Here’s a benchmark of ","type":"text"},{"code":"Float16","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" against ","type":"text"},{"code":"Float","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":":","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"WWDC20-10217-float16_benchmark","type":"image"}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Getting involved with Swift Numerics","anchor":"Getting-involved-with-Swift-Numerics"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Visit the GitHub page at ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics","overridingTitle":"github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics","isActive":true,"overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"github.com\/apple\/swift-numerics"}],"type":"reference"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Participate in "},{"identifier":"https:\/\/forums.swift.org","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" under the category “Related Projects”"}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Written By","anchor":"Written-By"},{"type":"row","numberOfCol